summary: Good Omens Book List: Crowley
title: Good Omens Book List: Crowley
body:
• The Ideal Husband by Oscar Wilde
  • Enemy Mine by Barry B. Longyear
  • Giovanni’s Room by James Baldwin
  • The Collected Poems of Oscar Wilde by Oscar Wilde
  • Broken Monsters by Lauren Beukes
  • The Master and Margarita by Mikhail Bulgakov
  • Heart of a Dog by Mikhail Bulgakov
  • The Fatal Eggs by Mikhail Bulgakov (Really anything by him because I can imagine Crowley appreciating the absurdity)
  • Calling A Wolf A Wolf by Kaveh Akbar
  • Twelfth Night by William Shakespeare
  • All the Rage by sam sax (Read “#Melancholia” and tell me you disagree)
  • Haunted by Chuck Palahniuk
  • In Love & Trouble by Alice Walker (Especially “Entertaining God” and “The Revenge of Hannah Kemhuff”)
  • The Country Wife by William Wycherley
  • Carmilla by Joseph Sheridan Le Fanu
  • Somebody to Love: The Life, Death, and Legacy of Freddie Mercury by Mark Langthorne and Matt Richards

summary: I caved and am about halfway through Good Omens! I shouldn’t be surprised at how good it is--but it’s so good! Nobody tell me,...

Crowley said to Hell that he...
body:
I have a headcanon that both Crowley and Aziraphale helped humanity to achieve (kinda) gay rights

Crowley said to Hell that he was helping to spike Heavens (because “sodomia” is not a Good Thing in Heavens y’know)

Aziraphale also participated but said to his bosses that Hell won this time (he did all he could so Hell would won this time)

In fact they both did it because they thought it was a right thing to do

title: Fear, Guiltiness and Love
body:
Pairing: Sam x Reader

Word Count: 473

Sam was distancing himself from you- from his brother. Something was bothering him and you knew you needed to find out what it was. You, Sam and Dean, had split up in order to cover the entire building. It was a big building with one little werewolf. You were the first one to come across the werewolf. You fired a shot at him and missed, which gave the rabid monster a head start in the wild goose chase throughout the building. You got caught up in the fight with the monster that you never have a second chance to fire a shot at him. The werewolf pushed you backwards. You struck your head against a metal pole and slid down the entire shelving unit. You lied there on the floor, in and out of consciousness, watching the werewolf stomp his way over to you. You hadn’t even heard the shot that was fired in order to kill him. You remembered seeing his cold, dead body hit the floor and then it all went black. You didn’t remember much of the fight when you woke up afterwards. Sam sat at your bedside, nervously bouncing his knee up and down.

“Sam?” You croaked.

“Y-yeah? I’m here.” He sniffed, grabbing a hold of your hand.

“Where am I?” You sat up a little bit, looking around the clean, white room.

Baby blue curtains were hung from the ceiling, attached to a track which allowed them to close off a certain area. You listened to the soft beep of your heart rate on the hospital monitor.

“What happened?” You groaned. “Mmm, my head.”

“You’re in the hospital, we were fighting a werewolf and you got hurt.” He sniffed, his bottom lip quivered like he was about to have a meltdown.

“Hey, hey. I’m gonna be okay. Talk to me, Sam… tell me what’s on your mind.”

“It’s my fault.” His voice was quiet and shaky. “I-I should’ve been there this time. You got hurt and I couldn’t do anything to help you. What kind of boyfriend am I if I can’t even take care of my own girlfriend?”

“Oh Sam, you’re the best boyfriend a girl could ever ask for.” You half smiled, making enough room on the bed for him.

Sam curled up on the bed next to you. You cuddled into him as you began to speak again.

“You did take care of me. You do take care of me. Sam, you were the one to save me. I’m forever grateful for all the times you’ve saved me.”

You gave him a soft and tender kiss, “Thank you for being my boyfriend, Sam.” You smiled up at him.  

It all made sense now. Why Sam was being so distant. He was afraid of you getting hurt because of him. You were glad that he talked to you and it was all out in the open.
